<DOCNO> AP890316-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the practice of disposing of pigeons by 
burying them alive was suspended after an official of the humane 
society of the united states contacted the mayors office 
guy hodge of the societys washington headquarters said he 
offered to travel to lexington and provide a blueprint for urban 
pigeon control that would include alternatives to burying the birds 
alive in the county landfill hodge said tuesday that the society 
might challenge the practice of burying live birds 
i would say certainly it violates the spirit if not the 
letter of the anticruelty law protecting animals in kentucky 
hodge said 
hodge said he knew of no other place in the nation where pigeons 
were buried alive john hadidian an urban wildlife biologist with 
the national park service in washington also said hed never heard 
of such a practice elsewhere 
lexington mayor scotty baesler who was in a meeting wednesday 
afternoon issued a statement that the burials were suspended he 
said he was unaware of the practice until it was reported wednesday 
in the lexington heraldleader 
robert myers of the lexington humane society said he was not 
aware the birds were being buried alive 
of course we see problems with that he said 
the city had a yearround trapping program and caught about 125 
birds a week said gayle wilson an aide in the department of public 
works he said the pigeons congregate on public buildings and leave 
smelly droppings 
they were removed by city sanitation workers tied in burlap bags 
and taken to the landfill where the bags were buried 
wilson said the method combined reasonable humaneness and 
convenience the method was inexpensive but that was not the 
deciding factor he said 
hodge said there is no evidence that killing pigeons eliminates 
the problem in the long run 
instead the humane society advocates taking measures to limit 
roosting spots pigeonproofing buildings by placing sharp 
spikes on roosting areas frightening the birds with noisemakers and 
passing laws to limit the food supply from citizens restaurants and 
other sources 
wilson said it was expensive to pigeonproof buildings and that 
pigeons were smart birds that soon learned to ignore noisemakers and 
predator decoys the only solution is to kill the birds he said 
tuesday 
wilson said that despite the apparent success of a pigeon shoot 
sunday in downtown somerset in southeast kentucky lexingtons 
pigeon problem was not bad enough to warrant blocking off downtown 
and shooting the birds 
i think the problem would have to be much more serious before 
wed close the downtown and let hunters cut loose on them 
wilson said 
carroll estes community development director in somerset said 
500 to 600 birds about half the pigeon population there were 
killed in sundays shoot and he expected half that many to be 
killed in a shoot scheduled saturday 
hodge said he had been trying wednesday to contact somerset 
officials to offer them a similar plan for pigeon control but had 
been unsuccessful 
estes who said he planned no further shoots after saturday 
because of the media aggravating you to death said he 
considered the method more humane than live burial 
im not out here choking ours to death he said 
</TEXT>
