<TEXT>
a 200yearold mainstay of treatment for congestive 
heart failure will continue to play its key role after research 
showed that a highly touted replacement is not as good for many 
patients experts say 
when testing began several years ago with the new drug called 
milrinone some experts predicted it would supplant digitalis as the 
medicine of choice for the 4 million americans with congestive heart 
failure 
the latest study published today compared milrinone to a form 
of digitalis called digoxin in people with mild to moderate heart 
failure 
although milrinone worked it was not as effective as digoxin 
those receiving it did worse and suffered more side effects 
the clinical wisdom of a few years ago that it would be a 
replacement for digitalis is not correct said dr robert 
dibianco who directed the study it will not replace digitalis 
experts said the findings were surprising and disappointing but 
in an editorial published with the study in the new england journal 
of medicine dr jay n cohn of the university of minnesota said 
the good news for now is that digoxin can be used with greater 
confidence in its efficacy 
doctors also said there should still be a place for milrinone 
because it may be used in people who cannot tolerate digitalis 
dibianco said he would like to be able to prescribe milrinone for 
such people but for the majority of my patients digitalis now 
even more firmly becomes the standard drug 
dibianco a researcher at washington adventist hospital in takoma 
park md was the studys principal author research was conducted 
on 230 patients at 32 hospitals 
an injected form of milrinone produced by sterling drug was 
approved by the us food and drug administration last year for 
shortterm treatment of acute heart failure however the fda has 
yet to clear the medicines pill form which was used in the latest 
study 
in the threemonth comparison study patients with mild to 
moderate heart failure were randomly assigned to take milrinone 
diuretics digoxin or a combination of these drugs 
the conditions of 20 percent of those taking milrinone 
deteriorated within two weeks after treatment began compared with 
only 3 percent of those receiving digoxin side effects of milrinone 
included palpitations irregular heartbeat lightheadedness low 
blood pressure nervousness and headaches 
among those who once suggested that milrinone might replace 
digitalis was dr donald s baim of beth israel hospital in boston 
his early results showed that the drug helped people with severe 
congestive heart failure who did not respond to other medicines 
although the latest results are disappointing he said i still 
believe that there is a clear beneficial role in the patient who has 
heart failure that is refractory to the conventional agents 
