<TEXT>
the worlds land areas have become wetter over 
the last century or so but the rainfall increases have skipped 
large areas of the planet according to a study released thursday 
south america and australia have seen measurable increases in 
precipitation since the late 1800s the national oceanic and 
atmospheric administration reported 
at the same time however there has been a decline in africa and 
in tropical areas of the northern hemisphere 
the analysis of rainfall patterns was compiled by noaas henry f 
diaz rs bradley of the university of massachusetts and jon 
eischeid of the university of colorado their findings are to be 
published in an upcoming issue of the journal of geophysical 
research 
the scientists looked at nearly a century of records diaz said 
the primary period of increasing rainfall in the southern hemisphere 
was from the 1940s to the mid1950 
in the northern hemisphere the overall trend is almost 
unchanged he said noting however that there seems to have been a 
decline in rainfall in northern tropical areas in the last 15 years 
or so 
rainfall patterns show substantial variability from time to time 
the scientists noted changing over periods of a decade or more 
thus they said it is difficult to determine whether rainfall 
has been affected by longterm phenomena such as that embodied in 
the greenhouse theory which predicts that changes in the atmosphere 
will cause worldwide temperatures to warm leading to changes in 
rainfall and other climate phenomena 
</TEXT>
