<TEXT>
three federal agencies proclaimed today that 
apples are safe for children to eat attempting to calm fears about 
a chemical used by some growers that has been linked to cancer and 
claims that preschoolers are especially vulnerable 
the federal government believes that it is safe for americans 
to eat apples said a joint statement by the environmental 
protection agency food and drug administration and agriculture 
department 
the agencies said there is no imminent hazard posed to 
children by the consumption of apples 
at a senate hearing fda administrator frank young noted that he 
moved swiftly to raise concerns about fruit imported from chile 
after traces of cyanide were found in two grapes he declared he 
would do the same if he thought apples were dangerous for children 
there has been growing concern among parents and school officials 
about whether children should continue eating apples and apple 
products until questions about the health questions 
at the center of the controversy is the chemical daminozide sold 
under the trade name alar which the epa said has caused cancer in 
test animals last month a private environmental group issued a 
report suggesting that children are especially at risk from alar 
because they consumer many times more apples and apple products 
compared to their weight than adults 
school systems in a number of cities including new york chicago 
and los angeles have stopped providing children apples after the 
report by the natural resources defense council was made public and 
the cbs program 60 minutes reported on the controversy 
in a statement the three federal agencies said the federal 
government encourages school systems and other responsible for the 
diets of children to continue to serve apples and other nutritious 
fruit to american children 
young said the reaction to claims that young children are exposed 
to a dangerous levels of alar in apples has caused a panic that 
is not warranted he said there is not a signficant risk at this 
time facing the american people in the consumption of apples 
john moore acting deputy epa administrator told the senate 
subcommittee on children families drugs and alcoholism that while 
the epa has conclude that daminozide causes cancer its continued 
use does not pose a threat that would warrant the chemical being 
ordered immediately off the market 
moore in his testimony criticized the nrdc studys risk estimates 
as not being scientifically sound and said the report has caused 
misinformation and fear to dominate the debate nevertheless 
moore said if daminozide were a newly introduced pesticide it would 
not be approved 
sen brock adams dwash suggested that the manufacturer of 
alar would do us all a public service if they suspended production 
of the product because the controversy is harming the apple 
industry 
adams said most growers in washington state do not use 
daminozide but there was no agreement among witnesses as to how 
widespread the use of the chemical actually is 
young said the fda has concluded that about 10 percent of the 
apples are sprayed with alar but the epa has cited a figure of 
about 5 percent consumer groups have claimed that spot checks have 
shown a use as high as 30 percent 
several senators said the controversy is threatening the apple 
industry the apple market is dead as a doornail right now across 
america said sen steven symms ridaho whose family owns an 
apple orchard 
