<TEXT>
major us jewish groups are calling on jews 
around the world to boycott meetings with pope john paul ii because 
the vatican has failed to remove a convent from the site of the nazi 
death camp at auschwitz the world jewish congress announced 
thursday 
the us section of the world jewish congress which represents 
34 american groups adopted a resolution that calls for wjc members 
in 70 countries to refrain from meetings with the pope during his 
frequent travels 
the resolution adopted at a meeting of organization leaders in 
new york will be introduced at the may 7 meeting of the wjcs 
international executive in montreal 
the resolution said the boycott call was an expression of 
anguish and moral distress at the roman catholic churchs failure 
to comply with a 1987 agreement that would remove the carmelite 
convent to grounds outside the extermination camp in poland 
the convent controversy is symptomatic of a clear pattern by 
the vatican to revise the history of the holocaust and the role of 
the church during that terrible period the resolution said pope 
pius xii has been widely criticized for failing to act or speak out 
against the nazis murder of 6 million jews during world war ii 
the clash over the convent comes at a time of increasing tensions 
between the world jewish community and the vatican nobel laureate 
elie wiesel a holocaust survivor and author recently accused pope 
john paul ii of trying to dejudaize the holocaust by ignoring 
jewish suffering in speeches and comments about that era 
jewish groups are also angry that the pope has met twice in the 
last three years with austrian president kurt waldheim who has been 
accused of complicity in nazi atrocities 
the convent at auschwitz was established in 1984 by a dozen 
carmelite nuns in a building the nazis had used to store poison gas 
canisters that action set of a storm of international protest from 
jews who wanted the camp site left undisturbed as a memorial to its 
victims 
jewish and catholic leaders met in geneva in 1987 and agreed that 
the convent would be removed by feb 22 1989 the church undertook 
in writing to move the nuns to nearby grounds outside the camp so 
they could continue their educational activities about the holocaust 
in recent months vatican officials have said a site had been 
chosen for the new convent one cleric said work on the building 
would soon be completed but a wjc delegation that visited the area 
in january said it had found no construction at all 
