<TEXT>
communist party leaders today adopted a sweeping 
reform program for the inefficient soviet agricultural system that 
they hope will end chronic food shortages 
the plan adopted by the plenary meeting of the partys 
300member central committee would give the nations farmers the 
right to lease stateowned land for life however it would also 
maintain the network of state and collective farms that have 
chronically failed to feed the soviet people 
the party also elected its 100 members to the congress of 
peoples deputies a new legislative body that will meet for the 
first time this spring among them was president mikhail s 
gorbachev 
the plenum acted after debating gorbachevs plan to give farmers 
longterm leases on stateowned land to make them more attentive and 
efficient 
gorbachev also says farmers should be given freedom to decide 
what to plant on that land rather than having that decided by the 
bureaucracy 
politburo member yegor k ligachev told a news conference the 
leases could be signed for any period of more than five years and be 
passed on to succeeding generations of farmers he said no one would 
be forced into leasing land 
he also said the giant state and collective farms would remain 
the backbone of the soviet agricultural system 
radical changes in rural life and production relations should 
be carried out on a purely voluntary basis without any kind of 
force or repressive methods ligachev said in his first appearance 
before foreign reporters 
setting targets for leasing would only encourage strongarm 
tactics to fulfill the plans ligachev said 
ligachev is the politburo member in charge of farm policy and is 
widely regarded as a conservative force on the politburo 
before the plenum he spoke out for including leasing in a wide 
variety of methods to improve agricultural production he said the 
approach to agriculture will include leasing selffinancing and 
greater democracy in rural life 
the plenum abolished the giant gosagroprom superministry in 
charge of agricultural policy and gorbachev interrupted its chief 
vsevolod murakovsky who spoke out in favor of continuing the system 
in which all local regions are required to send a percentage of 
their harvest to central authorities 
showing his impatience with domination of local producers by the 
central bureaucracy gorbachev interrupted again when another 
speaker brought up the issue of the government orders 
in a speech on wednesday gorbachev painted a bleak picture of 
soviet agriculture with chemically despoiled land deliberate 
destruction of sound system prevalent in the 1920s and massive 
investments gone sour the situation is so bad that it will be years 
before the country can feed itself he said 
gorbachevs detailed report on years of failed reforms made it 
clear that he believes nothing less than radical change will free 
soviets from rationing of meat and cheese now found in many cities 
his proposal to abolish a government superagency created in 1985 
to oversee the countrys farm sector was a tacit acknowledgement of 
the failure of even his early attempts to revitalize agriculture 
