<TEXT>
university researchers in massachusetts 
pennsylvania and michigan reported results of two separate 
experiments thursday which could someday lead to new drugs to use 
against cancer 
university of michigan researchers reported what they said was 
the first stimulation of the immune system in mucouslined tissues 
against a cancercausing chemical 
this could lead to inoculations that could keep some 
cancercausing chemicals and toxins from being absorbed by the body 
a team from harvard university and the university of 
pennsylvania reported tests of a complex compound that when given 
with certain steroid drugs is up to 1000 times more powerful than 
current drugs in inhibiting the growth of small capillary blood 
vessels that tumors need for growth 
without the steroids the compound is a powerful stimulator of 
capillary growth which is necessary for ovulation menstruation and 
growth of the placenta in women and wound repair in both sexes 
whether suppressing capillary growth is a fruitful anticancer 
strategy has to await safe and effective suppressors the 
harvardpennsylvania group said 
both reports were published in the issue of science magazine 
which is published friday 
many body tissues exposed to the outside environment are lined 
with mucous particularly the nose and mouth 
if those tissues are invaded by a virus a bacterially produced 
toxin or similar agent which might produce a cold or other illness 
they secrete antibodies if the virus reappears the antibodies bind 
to it and prevent its absorption as is believed to happen with the 
viruses that cause colds 
vaccines such as the sabin oral polio vaccine work in part by 
priming this secretory immune system one of several in the body to 
generate antibodies 
but ordinary chemical molecules are generally too small to elicit 
such a response 
at the university of michigan lawrence k silbart a 
toxicologist who is a research fellow in pathology and david f 
keren professor of pathology bound a powerful cause of cancer in 
laboratory animals 2acetylaminofluorene or aaf to the toxin 
produced by the choleracausing bacterium vibrio cholerae 
they measured absorption into the bloodstream of a radioactive 
derivative of the aaftoxin complex across the membrane of the 
intestines of rabbits immunized with the complex and compared that 
with the absorption of the same substance in a control group of 
rabbits immunized with an unrelated toxin absorption of aaf into 
the blood was more than twice in the control group as it was in the 
test group 
the article said the results suggest that oral vaccines against 
carcinogens and toxicants could be developed for humans 
as to the absorption after immunization ideally wed like to 
eliminate it completely said keren in an interview in nature 
youre going to be exposed to chronic low doses and you might see 
reductions of a factor of 100 or so 
this is the first hard evidence that you can make the secretory 
immune response and that it can interfere with absorption of 
the carcinogen but many years of work are needed to produce a 
useful vaccine he said 
the harvardpennsylvania team led by judah folkman professor of 
surgery at the harvard medical school noted that heparin a complex 
chemical used as an anticoagulant drug has been found to promote 
capillary growth by itself and to inhibit that growth when combined 
with certain steroids 
not all investigators have been able to find the anticapillary 
effect and the harvardpennsylvania team wrote that potent 
inhibition of angiogenesis capillary formation and growth is 
also subject to the variable activity of different heparin 
preparations 
those preparations have been nonuniform and heterogeneous in 
composition molecular size structure position of subtituents and 
sequence this heterogeneity probably accounts for the variability 
in findings of the effects of heparin 
the team used betacyclodextrin tetradecasulfate a 
doughnutshaped compound made up of seven repeating units of a 
substance called glucopyranose with two sulfate groups attached to 
each unit 
the hole in the doughnut is necessary to carry the steroid 
drug to the surface of the target cells the investigators theorized 
tested in chick embryos and rabbit corneas the activity of 
betacyclodestrin tetradecasulfate showed vesselsuppressing 
activity 100 to 1000 times that of commercially available 
heparin fully reproducible from one preparation to another 
in the corneas the substance used with cortexolone decreased 
vessel growth to 18 percent of that of untreated control eyes 
measured according to vessel length and to 8 percent according to 
the density of blood vessels by itself betacyclodestrin 
tetradecasulfate stimulated vessel length to 164 percent of 
untreated controls 
