the government lost money on timber sales in 
more than twothirds of the nations 120 national forests during 
fiscal 1988 but still recorded an overall profit of 3887 million 
the forest service said thursday 
in its second annual accounting of the costs and benefits of 
national forest timber sales the forest service said its timber 
sales program made a profit of 4422 million in 46 national 
forests mostly in the california washington oregon arizona new 
mexico and the parts of southeast 
the logging program in the other 74 national forests lost a total 
of 537 million officials said more than 80 percent of the 126 
billion board feet of timber harvested from national forests was 
taken from forests where revenues exceeded expenses 
peter m emerson chief economist and vice president for resource 
planning and economics for the wilderness society said the report 
reinforces the societys view that the forest services timber sales 
program is an environmentally destructive federal boondoggle 
the wilderness society has been urging the forest service for 
several years to halt timber sales in national forests where 
expenses exceed revenue the society contends that logging 
activities in such forests usually are the most damaging to the 
environment since the trees tend to be located in the most 
unapproachable areas 
