<TEXT>
black women are spending twice as many years 
living without a spouse than white women at least in part because 
they believe they have less financial incentive to get married or 
stay married a researcher says 
an ongoing study of the economic and other disparities between 
races determined that black women are catching up financially with 
black men at a rate much faster than the pay of white women is 
approaching that of white men 
the researcher university of michigan sociology professor 
reynolds farley said one obvious reason for that is that wages paid 
black men lag well behind those paid white men 
still he said black women often develop the perception it is 
not in their best financial interest to get or stay married and 
because of that they are waiting longer than white women to marry 
and are divorcing more frequently 
black women when they look around and think about getting 
married see that the pool of black men with high earnings is 
relatively small farley said in a telephone interview wednesday 
this gives them less of a financial incentive to get married or to 
remain married 
another reseacher interviewed thursday did not dispute farleys 
finding but said the underlying factor behind it was most likely 
years of wage discrimination against black men that has resulted in 
black women having a longer tradition of having to work than white 
women because of that black women have a greater sense of 
financial independence even if their wages are lower than those 
paid white women said phyllis palmer director of the womens 
studies program at george washington university 
i think its true that black mens low income affects the 
marriage rate of black women palmer said but its overly 
cynical to say money is the only thing that gets one married 
farley said that in 1987 30 percent of black women between the 
ages of 1544 were living with a husband compared with 52 percent 
in 1960 and 70 percent in 1950 fiftyfive percent of white women in 
that age bracket were living with a husband in 1987 down from 69 
percent in 1960 and 70 percent in 1950 
several studies have noted complaints by black women that there 
is a shortage of black males in the marriage pool but farley said 
that when numbers alone are considered those complaints are 
unfounded 
there have been nearly equal numbers of black men and women 
within each age group since the 1970s so there is not an absolute 
shortage of black men he said however the persistently high 
unemployment rate and limited earnings of black men may lead some 
black women to delay marriage and correspondingly some black men 
may hesitate to take on the financial obligations of a family 
data from 197580 indicate that black women on average will spend 
16 years of their 73year life span with a spouse while white women 
can expect to spend 33 of their expected 77 years with a mate 
farley said 
higher homicide and incarceration rates among blacks likely 
contribute to those numbers palmer said 
farleys data were compiled as part of a larger study he is 
conducting to determine why civil rights programs designed to bring 
blacks and other minorities on an equal economic footing with whites 
have failed to do so 
working with data from the census bureau and other sources 
reynolds determined that the average annual earnings of black women 
and white women are close 13800 for black women in 1987 and 
14700 for white women 
but earnings of black women are much closer to those of black 
men who made 18500 in 1987 while white women still lag well 
behind white men who made 28000 in 1987 
relative to the incomes of their potential mates black women 
are doing better than white women farley said 
</TEXT>
