here are some key dates in the chronology of 
warnings and terrorist threats surrounding the bombing of pan am 
flight 103 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
october west german authorities conducting raids discover a 
radiocassette player containing plastic explosives and a barometric 
timing device that could be set to detonate a bomb at a given 
altitude thirteen alleged members of the syrianbacked popular 
front for the liberation of palestinegeneral command guerrilla 
group are arrested 
nov 18 the date trans world airlines says the federal aviation 
administration told it of the bomb found in west germany 
nov 22 the british department of transport issues a bulletin 
via telex to relevant security authorities reporting discovery 
of bomb in west germany it now says that warning would have been 
circulated by the federal aviation authority to us airlines and 
other agencies that would need to know 
dec 5 the us embassy in helsinki is warned in a telephone 
call of a plot to bomb a pan am airliner on a frankfurtus flight 
during a twoweek period in december the federal aviation 
administration issues an intelligence alert that there might be 
a bomb attempt against a pan am flight from frankfurt 
dec 9 us authorities notify the british government of the 
dec 5 warning to the us embassy in helsinki 
dec 19 the british department of transport repeats its nov 22 
warning with additional details and a photo of the radiocassette 
recorder as it would look if it was wired to explode the bulletin 
is addressed to all british airports plus british and american 
airlines and el al of israel air india and south african airways 
dec 21 flight 103 is destroyed over lockerbie scotland 
killing all 259 people aboard and 11 on the ground 
dec 23 a british official says the government issued no public 
warnings about the dec 5 threat made against pan am flights because 
the information was considered confidential british airports were 
not told about the information passed on by us authorities 
apparently because the threat did not specifically mention britain 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan 17 the date pan am says it received a memo by mail from 
the british department of transport dated dec 19 
mar 15 the british department of transport first announces it 
alerted airlines and airports on dec 19 about a possible terrorist 
attack with precise details similar to the device that destroyed 
flight 103 
