<TEXT>
a twoyear legal battle over the states 
refusal to allow ceremonial sweat lodges for indian inmates at utah 
state prison ended thursday when a federal judge ruled the ban is 
unconstitutional 
applause broke out in the packed courtroom and american indians 
from several different tribes chanted and pounded drums outside 
after us district judge j thomas greene struck down the ban in a 
bench ruling on motions for summary judgment 
im grateful the words are kind of hard to come by at this 
time because the feeling is so good said george a roybal an 
assiniboine sioux who as a utah prison inmate in march 1987 
initiated the lawsuit with five other inmates 
what this thing is all about is us trying to help our people to 
help themselves he said 
the utah department of corrections had contended the sweat lodge 
which tribal officials contend is central to purification and 
ceremonial rites dating back 40000 years threatened security 
because the lodge must be dark and enclosed 
but greene cited two us supreme court rulings and the success 
of sweat lodges in 19 other state prison systems and two federal 
penitentiaries in rejecting arguments that the small willow and 
canvas structures posed a security risk 
the judge said the prohibition was unreasonable and resulted in 
the native american religion not being accommodated to the extent 
other religions are 
the sweat lodge will simply be another chapel located within 
the prison greene said 
michael obrien an attorney representing the american civil 
liberties union said guards could monitor ceremonies and prison 
officials could impose limitations such as searches and requirements 
that the lodge be dismantled after each service 
the record is clear that 19 other states and the federal prison 
system accommodate these sweat lodges without risk to security 
obrien said 
telephone messages left at the office of joseph tesch the 
associate utah attorney general who defended the case for the state 
were not immediately returned 
the aclu was one of several groups that provided legal or moral 
support to the inmates cause the native american rights fund and 
the giant navajo nation also joined the plaintiffs in the lawsuit 
while the central salt lake city council of churches representing 
pastors from six denominations urged gov norm bangerter to 
intervene on the inmates behalf 
prison officials had earlier offered to allow a modified sweat 
lodge equipped with a window and mechanical heating instead of the 
required heated rocks but plaintiffs attorney danny quintana 
called the suggestion blasphemous 
greene concurred telling associate utah attorney general joseph 
tesch at one point its like saying to a christian you can have 
a ceremony but dont mention christ 
attorneys for the navajo nation which manages sweat lodge 
programs for 500 inmates in federal and state systems argued that 
the ceremonies are vital to rehabilitation 
the sweat lodge provides a link between the incarcerated indian 
inmate and his tribe and the program administered by the navajos 
offers drug and alcohol counseling in addition to spiritual 
guidance said navajo lawyer lee bergen 
</TEXT>
