<TEXT>
ante markovic took office as premier 
thursday and promised marketoriented reforms to rescue yugoslavia 
from an economic decline that began with the death of president tito 
in 1980 
markovic a successful businessman said in his inaugural speech 
a freemarket economy is the ultimate achievement of mankind for 
which no alternative has yet been found 
he also said there is no solution to the economic crisis 
without the strengthening of political democracy in the country 
and advocated creation of a new modern socialist system 
a new cabinet much trimmer than before also was sworn in 
markovics government has 19 ministers compared to 29 under branko 
mikulic who resigned dec 30 because his government could not 
resolve the economic crisis 
this balkan nation of 23 million must undergo fundamental 
change in order achieve economic revival markovic said 
inflation has reached an annual rate of 346 percent and 
yugoslavia owes 21 billion to foreign creditors labor unrest and 
ethnic conflict have become chronic 
much of the recent ethnic trouble has involved the southern 
province of kosovo where ethnic albanians form a majority of 90 
percent about 2000 albanian miners have been on strike in kosovo 
for nearly a month 
the government raised the prices of gasoline and diesel fuel 
thursday for the third time this year by an average of 187 
percent the official news agency tanjug reported 
yugoslavs whose average monthly pay is equivalent to 120 now 
must pay about 182 a gallon for gasoline 
markovic indicated he would seek closer links to the west 
including greater economic cooperation with the european economic 
community 
he advocates reshaping the banking system along western lines 
creating a stock market and ending state subsidies to companies that 
lose money 
yugoslavia left the soviet bloc in 1948 and is a founding member 
of the organization of nations that profess nonalignment 
mikulics government was the first to resign since the communist 
party gained power after world war ii the new one is a mix of 
prominent politicians and technocrats with only two ministers 
retaining the seats they occupied in mikulics government 
foreign minister budimir loncar and the defense minister gen 
veljko kadijevic carry over but defense minister dobrosav culafic 
lost his job 
culafic was severely criticized for his handling of ethnic strife 
in kosovo the ancient heart of serbia the remaining serbian 
minority accuses the ethnic albanians of discrimination 
gen petar gracanin president of serbia is the new interior 
minister serbia is the largest of yugoslavias six republics and 
kosovo is an autonomous province within it 
