police caught a palestinian terrorist group with a radiocassette 
player containing explosives and a barometric device that would 
detonate a bomb at high altitude according to british and west 
german officials 
we sent advice to the relevant security authorities the 
transport department said in its statement they were told what to 
look for the american authorities would have done the same for 
american airlines 
in washington state department spokesman charles redman said the 
arrests in west germany also prompted the faa issued a warning nov 
18 that told of the terrorist group the existence of this bomb 
its characteristics and to advise that increased security measures 
should be introduced to counter this threat 
this bulletin remains in effect today he added 
on dec 5 the us embassy in helsinki was warned in a telephone 
call of a plot to bomb a pan am airliner on a frankfurtus flight 
during a twoweek period in december the faa issued an 
intelligence alert that there might be a bomb attempt against a 
pan am flight from frankfurt 
speaking on bbctv channon said the nov 22 warning was sent to 
british airlines and airports and of course the federal aviation 
administration sent out their own warning to the american airlines 
asked about pan ams statement that it didnt get the second 
warning until jan 17 channon said there is no importance to it 
whatsoever all it contained virtually was a color photograph of a 
cassette player and a few more unimportant pieces of information 
about how a bomb in frankfurt had been constructed 
he said the evidence that the bomb was placed aboard the plane at 
londons heathrow airport is very slender indeed all the 
evidence seems to point the other way 
asked if this meant he was blaming us and west german 
authorities for failing to prevent the bombing he said i dont 
make any comment about that thats for the investigators to decide 
and for the police west german authorities say there is no firm 
evidence that the bomb was smuggled aboard in frankfurt 
in frankfurt manfred langendorf chief of the hesse state 
interior ministrys office for airport security said thursday all 
airlines operating in west germany including pan am were told in 
early november about the radiocassette player containing explosives 
david wilshire of britains governing conservative party who 
follows air transport affairs denied suggestions authorities simply 
dropped a highly sensitive warning into the christmas mail deluge 
