<TEXT>
advocates for the homeless and state and 
congressional housing experts on wednesday criticized a federal 
panel charged with coordinating programs for the homeless saying it 
had done virtually nothing to provide shelter for people without 
housing 
the complaints about the interagency council on the homeless came 
at a joint hearing of two house subcommittees wednesday while the 
senate subcommittee on housing introduced legislation its sponsors 
touted as the framework for a new national housing strategy 
the litany of the councils failures began in the opening 
statement from rep cardiss collins dill who chairs the 
government activities and transportation subcommittee of the 
committee on government operations 
it didnt hold meetings it didnt set policy it didnt 
coordinate federal programs it didnt assess the needs of the 
homeless it didnt recommend legislative changes or funding 
levels said collins 
it has failed almost completely to carry out the mandates set 
for it by congress she said 
the council established in 1987 by title ii of the mckinney act 
was given the responsibility to coordinate 20 new programs created 
by the law monitor implementation of programs to the homeless 
disseminate information about the programs to local governments and 
nonprofit organizations serving the homeless and help them develop 
new programs 
but rep tom lantos dcalif chairman of the employment and 
housing subcommittee and cohost of wednesdays hearing said much of 
the information that homeless providers needed to apply for mckinney 
funds was provided instead by the national governors association 
wendy adler of the nga testified that after receiving numerous 
requests from the states for information she had developed and 
updated three times a report on the status of programs under the 
mckinney act and related legislation 
this publication contains the type of information the council 
should be disseminating said adler chiding the council for not 
fulfilling its most basic mandate 
other witnesses said the council has failed to develop a complete 
staff identify regional and field coordinators for programs and to 
clarify their duties focused too much on the development of an 
electronic data base which homeless providers could not use missed 
application deadlines met only five times in 18 months and 
produced only three monthly newsletters which contained useless 
information 
the council comprised of the heads or their designees of 10 
cabinet departments and five independent agencies was headed by 
former housing secretary sam pierce lantos joked that the late 
elvis presley had been seen more often on capitol hill than pierce 
the duties with which the council is charged and its ability to 
carry them out must be brought into balance said cassandra moore 
the councils former executive director 
she said congress gave the council broad authority to develop 
programs and issue timetables but not the power or resources to 
fulfill its mandate as described in mckinney 
moore also recommended increasing the staff size and removing the 
council from under the administrative wing of the department of 
housing and urban development she said hud had been resistant to 
sharing information on homelessness and virtually noncommunicative 
but hud had provided administrative support to the council on a 
continuing basis according to james stimpson a deputy assistant 
housing secretary 
he said the new administration has made homelessness one of its 
highest priorities and sees the council as an effective partner 
in addressing the problem 
</TEXT>
