<TEXT>
a fraud probe into the chicago futures 
exchanges coincides with a congressional review of the commodity 
futures trading commission and has raised new questions about its 
ability to police abuses 
theoretically congress could decide not to reauthorize the 
15yearold regulatory body but cftc officials say accusations that 
they have failed to curb corruption in the freewheeling futures pits 
arent true 
weve had these same kinds of criticisms from the start said 
john v rainbolt a washington lawyer for commodities traders and 
brokers and a cftc vice chairman 
everybodys got a vested interest in doing or saying whatever 
they need to promote their particular cause he said in a recent 
interview its a combination of bureaucratic sour grapes 
regulatory competition and power plays in congress 
the cftc was created in 1974 to enforce federal laws regulating 
the futures and options markets congress reauthorized it in 1978 
1982 and 1986 lawmakers are considering legislation this year to 
extend its authority through 1994 
the house agriculture committee which oversees the commission 
planned on a quick reauthorization process 
however its chairman rep eligio kika de la garza dtexas 
ordered an indepth review after learning of an fbi investigation of 
alleged fraud and illegal trading on chicago futures markets the 
nations largest 
the fbi probe reportedly involves allegations that brokers and 
traders cheated customers out of millions of dollars in deals on the 
chicago mercantile exchange and chicago board of trade 
an immediate question that surfaced in the probe was why the cftc 
didnt root out such corruption if it existed 
futures trading had been regulated since 1936 by the commodity 
exchange authority but rainbolt said the agency with 161 
employees in the basement of the department of agriculture and no 
real authority at all was unable to keep pace with growth in the 
industry 
from 1969 to 1973 volume in regulated commodities doubled and 
trading in unregulated commodities quadrupled to create what a 
congressional report said was a 400 billion industry 
with growth came the potential for abuses such as the sale of 
unregulated options by a california company that parlayed a 1000 
investment into a multimilliondollar company by using new 
investors money to pay old customers 
the firms collapse in the early 1970s resulting in more than 
71 million in customer losses was cited as the catalyst for 
congressional action to scrap the exchange authority and create the 
cftc 
in a report on its activities in 1988 cftc chairman wendy l 
gramm said the commission assessed more than 2 million in civil 
penalties for violating commodities laws last year decided more 
than 500 reparation cases and issued more than 185 opinions and 
orders 
nonetheless critics have branded the commission as lax and 
excessively reliant on industry selfregulation 
the exchanges have their own operating rules established in 
alliance with the industryoperated national futures association 
it in turn acts with approval of the federal commission 
this whole system was born when the emphasis was to 
deregulate said rep glenn english dokla chairman of the 
subcommittee investigating the cftc the issue as we look at the 
whole system is to reassess the entire deregulation mentality is 
it adequate does it need to be changed 
futures industry officials contend selfregulation works well 
some say the cftc is too meddlesome now 
speaking as one of the regulated i get mad at the cftc and 
disagree with them every day said john m damgard president of 
the futures industry association trade group and a commodity 
purchaser himself 
but the relationship is not so adversarial that were unwilling 
to admit we have somebody over there whos smart who understands 
our industry and who will listen damgard said that is an 
agency that over the last 15 years has matured into one of the 
finest government agencies we have 
even if lawmakers reauthorize the cftc some predict the debate 
will resurrect jursidictional arguments over who should regulate 
futures trading the cftc or the rival securities and exchange 
commission 
the sec has been a better regulator said rep jim cooper 
dtenn you need a strong regulatory body regardless of what its 
initials are to police a group of very impressive and sometimes 
greedy traders and brokers 
