<TEXT>
farmers are expected to boost plantings of corn 
and some other major crops this spring and agriculture department 
analysts say fuel needed to do their field work will cost more 
again 
energy prices overall are expected to edge up in 1989 due to 
higher crude oil prices the departments economic research service 
said in the march issue of agricultural outlook magazine 
farm fuel prices rose slightly in 1988 the report said as 
a result of higher crude oil prices in the last quarter of 1988 
average petroleum product prices paid by farmers should rise 
throughout 1989 
the report said the increase in crude oil prices during last 
years fourth quarter was prompted by an agreement of the 
organization of petroleum exporting countries to hold down 
production 
under opecs agreement in november there would be a price target 
of 18 per barrel and a reduction in output from the 17year high of 
225 million barrels per day to 185 million per day in the first 
six months of 1989 
the agreement also brought iraq back into the cartel with a quota 
equivalent to that of iran the report said 
according to department of energy forecasts economic growth of 
about 25 percent will offset higher crude oil prices and us 
petroleum consumption will therefore inch up about 1 percent this 
year 
the report said that for the first time since 1980 domestic 
petroleum demand last year averaged more than 17 million barrels a 
day refiners paid an average of 14 per barrel in the last half of 
1988 down 25 percent from 1987 prices 
but prices surged near the end of 1988 and west texas 
intermediate crude reached 18 per barrel in january 1989 the 
report said crude oil prices are expected to range from 15 to 
20 per barrel in 1989 
meanwhile us domestic production will probably slacken again 
this year to about 8 million barrels a day down 200000 from last 
year and 1988 output of 82 million barrels a day was the lowest in 
24 years 
expanding demand and decreasing domestic production are 
expected to boost us net imports in 1989 to 68 million barrels 
per day or 39 percent of domestic consumption the report said 
this rate may be compared with a record high import of 86 million 
barrels per day in 1977 and a low of 43 million in 1985 
the energy supply and price outlook for us agriculture mostly 
reflects world market conditions currently characterized by 
abundant oil supplies and higher prices 
in 1989 farmers can expect plentiful supplies of diesel fuel 
gasoline and lp liquefied petroleum gas but at slightly higher 
prices than last year the report said 
yet the combined use of gasoline and diesel fuel by farmers has 
declined in recent years because of improved farm production 
technology shifts from gasoline to more efficient diesel units and 
greatly reduced crop plantings 
although acres planted greatly influences the fluctuations in 
farm energy use other factors also have contributed to the 
decline the report said continued replacement of older 
gasoline machines with dieselpowered machines particularly in the 
production of cotton rice and some minor crops has resulted in 
greater use of diesel fuel 
besides acreage cutbacks under some government crop programs 
last years droughtreduced yields also contributed to an estimated 
5 percent reduction in farm fuel use in 1988 the report said lower 
grain moisture levels at harvest also reduced energy requirements 
but expenditures for farm energy gasoline diesel fuel lp and 
electricity were about 7 billion last year up 3 percent from 
1977 because of higher prices and greater reliance on electricity 
in 1989 energy expenditures which comprise about 55 percent 
of total farm production expenses are projected to jump 7 percent 
to 75 billion largely due to an expected 4 percent to 11 percent 
increase in planted area of the eight major crops the report said 
this will offset longterm reductions in fuel use related to 
conservation primarily from 28 million acres of land taken from 
production under the conservation reserve program 
