nationwide say auditors for the general accounting office the 
irs is correct only 60 percent of the time not the 69 percent 
claimed by the irs less than a week ago some of the answers that 
irs considers correct could lead taxpayers to foul up their returns 
gao said 
robert lebaube irs director of taxpayer services quarreled with 
the gao estimate but only slightly as far as the irs is 
concerned whether we are answering 30 percent of the questions 
wrong or 40 percent of the questions wrong either number is 
absolutely unacceptable he told the house government operations 
consumer subcommittee wednesday 
the irs own tests of its telephoneassistance system indicate a 
performance no better than last years even though employees have 
had an extra year to acquaint themselves with the big 1986 tax 
overhaul while the irs figures it is correct 69 percent of the time 
nationally in some of the 29 calling sites the accuracy rate is in 
the 50s and in others it is in the 70s lebaube said 
he did not identify those areas 
in an effort to improve performance lebaube said the irs is 
switching to a more permanent work force hiring fewer people to 
work only during the filing season the agency also is assigning 
more supervisors and using new procedures to discover problem areas 
of tax law that are causing most problems for the telephone 
assistors 
lebaube advised taxpayers who call the irs tollfree numbers to 
write down their question the date and name of the person who 
provided the answer if an answer leads to an incorrect tax return 
and the taxpayer produces such a record lebaube said the irs will 
waive any penalty 
the assistors are not properly trained to answer questions 
right 100 percent of the time asked rep matthew martinez 
dcalif that to me is really an intolerable situation 
the irs blames a complicated tax law for part of the problem as 
well as the frequency of changes in the law gao has said some irs 
employees are reluctant to probe for additional information from 
taxpayers before answering their tax questions 
the irs has about 5000 employees answering telephoned tax 
questions during this filing season about 1500 of them are 
temporaries all are required to have at least a high school 
education and receive at least five weeks tax training 
gao complaints that the irs was overstating its accuracy rate 
prompted chairman doug barnard jr dga to call his subcommittee 
into session for a rare public airing of a dispute between two 
government agencies 
gao and irs agreed to work together on one test of the 
telephoneassistance system and hammered out 62 questions that irs 
officials are expected to ask clandestinely about 15000 times this 
filing season 
gao and irs agreed to score answers in only three ways correct 
correct and complete or incorrect after the tests got under way 
the irs wanted a fourth grade an answer that while not technically 
correct likely would not result in a faulty return 
gao refused to go along contending some of those answers from 
irs employees were potentially misleading irs insisted and on its 
own beganscoring those answers which were 88 percent of the total 
as correct 
thus gao came up with an accuracy rate of 604 percent irs 
added the 88 percent in the fourth category and reached a total 
accuracy rate of 698 percent 
changing the method of judging the system in the middle of the 
test raises questions about the validity of its the irss 
reported results and whether it is making progress toward improving 
the accuracy of its responses said jennie stathis of gao 
it was not our intent to mislead anyone lebaube told the 
subcommittee in retrospect and in fairness to gao we probably 
should have announced both numbers 
