<TEXT>
its been a year since rebellious executives 
walked out of advertising agency lord geller federico einstein inc 
to start their own a split that has left two emotionally scarred 
rivals and courtroom accusations of business sabotage 
lord gellers biggest client international business machines 
corp took its business elsewhere a legal dispute on the breakup 
remains unresolved two agencies now use the lord name in their 
logos 
moreover lord geller and the new agency lord einstein oneill amp 
partners combined handle only about 60 percent of the business and 
employ only about twothirds as many people as lord geller did 
before the breakup 
the saga has drawn attention outside the advertising world 
because it has raised questions about the impact of executive 
defections in other service industries such as law and accounting 
some ad agency folks took delight in the courage the breakaway 
executives showed in leaving citing a desire for autonomy but at 
the same time they sympathized with those left behind 
a marketing consultant who advises advertisers about selecting an 
ad agency said the lingering legal controversy about the breakup may 
be frightening some potential clients from considering either agency 
in making a search for a new agency a company is looking for a 
long term stable relationship and i think both agencies at the 
moment are viewed as kind of unstable agencies said stanley 
canter of canter achenbaum associates 
lord geller however insists it has stabilized with billings of 
50 million and a payroll of 100 people down from 212 million in 
billings and 320 employees before the breakup 
billings reflect the amount of money advertisers pay for 
broadcast and published ads agencies often get a percentage of 
billings for their work 
lord einstein said its growth from zero to 75 million in 
billings and 82 employees in its first year makes it one of the 
fastest growing startups 
of those employed at lord geller before the breakup between 65 
and 70 still work there while about 40 are working for lord 
einstein about 210 have gone elsewhere either because they were 
laid off or quit 
ad industry analysts say the deep pockets of lord gellers 
parent the britainbased wpp group may guarantee its survival 
wpps chief executive martin sorrell is believed to be committed to 
maintaining lord geller as a second ad network separate from wpps 
other agency j walter thompson co 
lord einstein also has a powerful partner the ad agency young amp 
rubicam which holds a 49 percent stake in the new agency 
richard j lord helped found lord geller federico einstein inc 
in 1967 five years later lord and his partners sold the agency to 
