two newspaperbased conglomerates controlled by 
canadas thomson family announced wednesday they plan to merge 
operations into a giant media company worth about 75 billion 
the merger is subject to approval by minority shareholders in the 
two companies thomson newspapers ltd and international thomson 
organisation ltd 
the thomson family controls 61 percent of thomson newspapers ltd 
which publishes 40 canadian daily newspapers and 116 dailies in 
the united states family members control 735 percent of 
international thomson organisation ltd with newspaper and other 
media interests in britain and the united states 
the new company to be called thomson corp will have a head 
office in toronto and an executive office in new york city 
officials said at a news conference 
the merged company would have had 1988 sales of 47 billion 
earnings from continuing operations of 380 million and net income 
of 436 million 
the companies expect to have a detailed proposal within 30 days 
on how to carry out the merger officials said ken thomson who now 
chairs each company would be chairman of thomson corp and top 
management would remain 
the merger will capitalize on the unique strengths of thomson 
newspapers and international thomson to build a combined 
organization with even stronger foundations and better future 
prospects ken thomson said in a release 
together the companies employ more than 40000 people including 
5700 in canada no jobs will be eliminated in the merger officials 
said 
the merger will assure that we can more efficiently pursue 
further organic growth and acquisitions in both daily newspapers and 
specialized information and publishing businesses ken thomson 
said 
separately international thomson which also has interests in 
travel and airline businesses reported its profit rose 238 
percent in the year ended dec 31 
international thomson reported earnings of 229 million for the 
year on sales of 374 billion up from a profit of 185 million on 
sales of 311 billion a year earlier 
operating profit was up by 25 percent in the information and 
publishing segment and 304 percent in the leisure travel business 
international thomson completed the sale of its oil and gas 
interests to lasmo north sea plc completed march 6 the company 
previously announced it had an estimated gain of 475 million from 
the sale 
