<TEXT>
the futures industry will ultimately be 
strengthened if its leaders take a direct approach to issues raised 
by a federal investigation of commodity trading fraud the head of 
the industrys largest trade association said today 
we cant make the chicago investigation go away but in the end 
it will become one of those events in our history which hardens the 
steel from which we will build the futures industry of the 1990s 
said david ganis chairman of the futures industry association 
in his keynote speech at the opening of the groups annual 
meeting here ganis said the futures industry association is 
committed to promoting the highest ethical standards within the 
industry and will support all appropriate actions to protect the 
interest of the customers who rely on these markets 
trust is the very cornerstone of our ability to do business 
ganis told more than 1000 brokerage executives exchange officials 
and regulators attending the meeting at the posh boca raton hotel 
and club 
the meeting follows by two months the disclosure of an undercover 
federal probe of suspected fraud at the chicago board of trade and 
the chicago mercantile exchange the worlds two largest futures 
exchanges 
no charges have yet been issued in connection with the probe 
anton valukas the us attorney in chicago would not comment on 
rumors circulating among defense lawyers that six people would soon 
be charged 
the probe is believed to be targeting as many as 100 traders 
suspected of systematically cheating customers out of millions of 
dollars while executing their orders on the trading floors of the 
two chicago exchanges 
futures are contracts to buy and sell commodities and financial 
instruments at a specified price on a future date 
the investigation has focused attention on certain trading 
practices that can lead to cheating critics say 
chief among these is dual trading the longestablished practice 
among floor brokers of trading for their own accounts and their 
customers accounts at the same time 
ganis said the commodity futures trading commission a federal 
regulatory agency has asked his association to submit its own 
analysis of dual trading the cftc is seeking similar responses from 
futures exchanges in chicago and new york 
ganis who heads northern futures corp a chicagobased futures 
brokerage also said the federal investigation calls into question 
the adequacy of selfregulation of the futures industry 
under the existing selfregulatory system the cftc allows 
individual exchanges to make and administer their own trading rules 
cftc chairman wendy gramm who also spoke at the the meeting this 
morning said selfregulation had worked well in the past and called 
for renewed diligence among futures exchanges and brokerage firms in 
detecting and punishing wrongdoing 
i know that you have the incentive to root out fraud and abuse 
in these markets she said so do we and we will continue to be 
aggressive in this regard 
</TEXT>
