<TEXT>
spending for newspaper advertising rose 61 
percent to an estimated 312 billion in 1988 the smallest 
percentage gain in 13 years an industrybacked research 
organization said thursday 
the increase was down from a 90 percent rise in 1987 and was the 
smallest advance since a 50 percent rise in the recession year of 
1975 
the newspaper advertising bureau inc said preliminary estimates 
indicate spending for retail advertising the largest category for 
newspapers rose 40 percent to 1584 billion last year 
classified ad spending rose 101 percent to 1177 billion and 
national ad spending was up 26 percent to 359 billion 
media analysts have blamed the sluggish growth in retail ad 
spending partly on recent consolidation in the retailing business 
they said retailers also were reluctant to boost ad spending in 
the wake of the october 1987 stock market crash because of 
uncertainty earlier in the year about how the crash would affect 
consumer spending patterns 
retail ad spending grew only 17 percent in the second quarter of 
1988 for instance but picked up in the last half of the year 
rising 44 percent in the third quarter and 52 percent for the 
fourth quarter 
overall ad spending in newspapers was up 66 percent in the 
fourth quarter 
