panasonic co will issue refunds to about 
687000 consumers across the country as part of a 16 million 
pricefixing settlement agreed to this week new york attorney 
general robert abrams said wednesday 
the refunds range from 17 to 45 for products such as 
videocassette recorders cordless telephones answering machines and 
stereo equipment marketed under the panasonic or technics brand 
name abrams said 
the company last year pressured retailers to charge a certain 
price for some of its most popular products threatening to cut off 
their supply if they didnt comply he said 
the settlement worked out by abrams office and panasonics 
parent company matsushita electric corporation of america was 
announced in january but was formally accepted tuesday by officials 
in 48 other states and the district of columbia he said hawaii 
which deals with a separate panasonic subsidiary is not covered by 
the agreement 
consumers who purchased products between march 1 and august 31 
1988 will be eligible for the refunds abrams said 
panasonic agreed not to engage in the alleged activities for five 
years but did not admit to any wrongdoing 
