<TEXT>
the poisoning of grapes from chile poses a 
highprofile threat to a business that has grown to 900 million a 
year by using southern hemisphere farmers to put fruit on american 
tables all winter 
american importers and chilean farmers worry that if the cyanide 
sabotage case isnt solved soon they could lose the market for the 
25 percent of their crop still on trees or aboard usbound ships 
the tampering which prompted the food and drug administration to 
recommend pulling grapes nectarines pears and other chilean winter 
fruit from market shelves also might give the business a permanent 
public relations black eye one big importer said 
i think its a major major overreactionan entire industry 
is being destroyed los angeles importer rick eastes said tuesday 
eastes manager for the david oppenheimercalifornia import firm 
munched a couple of red flame seedless grapes from chile for 
reporters tuesday to underscore his anger over the fdas nosell 
recommendation 
the fda advised grocers to pull chilean fruit from the shelves 
tuesday after tests in philadelphia found cyanide at far below 
harmful levels had apparently been put in two clusters of grapes 
virtually all the socalled summer fruit on american grocery 
shelves this time of year is from chile whose farmers have learned 
to exploit the southern hemisphere growing season that is a mirror 
image of that in the north 
from a trickle of grape imports in the 1950s the business has 
grown to projected shipments this year with a retail value of 900 
million said caryl saunders a san francisco spokeswoman for the 
industry 
in 1979 when imports were starting to gain momentum the retail 
value of chilean grapes and stone fruit was 72 million said ms 
saunders by 1988 that had climbed to 600 million 
more than 100 ships full of chilean fruit are expected to land 
this year to be distributed nationwide from the ports of 
philadelphia long beach calif and tampa and cape canaveral in 
florida 
the business is organized by the growers under the banner of the 
chilean winter fruit association and the importers called the 
american produce association 
that loose alliance carefully orchestrates the traffic to avoid 
ruffling the feathers of american farmers 
grapes which make up threequarters of the shipments are 
carefully withheld until the last california emperor grapes clear 
the supermarkets usually sometime in december grape shipments are 
cut off earlier than would be decreed by nature in late april 
when the first california grapes make their way to market 
there is little overlap in growing season for nectarines and 
other fruit so there is less potential for conflict with american 
growers ms saunders said 
