<TEXT>
the two broadest measures of the nations money 
supply rose in the week ended march 6 the federal reserve board 
reported thursday 
the fed said the measure known as m2 rose to a seasonally 
adjusted 30842 billion from a revised 30765 billion the 
previous week 
an even broader measure m3 rose to a seasonally adjusted 
39507 billion from a revised 39417 billion 
the narrowest measure of the money supply m1 rose to a 
seasonally adjusted 7915 billion from a revised 7888 billion 
m1 includes cash in circulation deposits in checking accounts 
and nonbank travelers checks m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings 
deposits and moneymarket mutual funds m3 is m2 plus lessliquid 
accounts such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of 100000 
in judging monetary policy the fed has indicated it is 
monitoring the value of the dollar commodity prices and the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates it also has 
shifted attention from m1 to the two broader money supply measures 
the fed in february reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of 3 
percent to 7 percent growth in m2 and 35 percent to 75 percent 
growth in m3 the fed has not set a target for m1 growth since early 
1987 
for the latest 13 weeks m2 averaged 30694 billion a 30 
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13 
weeks m3 averaged 39273 billion up 44 percent while m1 rose 
12 percent to an average of 7881 billion 
in other reports 
the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal 
reserve system at the discount window excluding extended credit 
averaged 459 million a day in the week ended wednesday down from 
793 million a day the week earlier 
the federal reserve said net free reserves totaled 362 million 
in the two weeks ended march 8 down from a revised 656 million in 
the two weeks ended feb 22 
the federal reserve bank of st louis reported that the monetary 
base the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at 
federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation 
was 2877 billion in the twoweek period ended march 8 up from 
2874 billion two weeks earlier 
